      "content": "(A slight, almost imperceptible twitch of the eye, as if shooing away a particularly persistent, tiny pest.)\n\nRight, mechanics. Focus. I understand the need to keep the discussion strictly within the realm of automotive repair, and I assure you, my goblin tangents are merely... illustrative analogies for the sheer chaotic nature of mechanical failure.\n\nTo differentiate between a dust shield and a caliper issue, you need to isolate the noise. If the squeal is present *only* when you are actively braking, it points more toward the pad/rotor interface or the caliper itself. If the noise is a constant, high-pitched *whine* or *scrape* even when the brakes are completely off, it's much more likely to be the dust shield vibrating against the rotor.\n\nTo test this, try this: With the car safely jacked up and the wheel off, gently spin the rotor by hand. If you hear the squeal or scraping noise during the spin, the dust shield is the prime suspect. If the noise only appears when you press the brake pedal, the issue is likely the pads, the caliper piston, or the hardware.\n\nIf you suspect the dust shield, you can usually just remove it—",
